message: Focus on cutting 'soft' items (natural and artificial). A common high-value strategy is: Cut an artificial soft item (e.g., newspaper, paper, sponge, ribbon) + Cut a natural soft item (e.g., leaf, flower, mushroom) -> Combine them (often 80 points) -> Add the frame (often 100 points). Combining two artificial soft items (e.g., cut newspaper + cut yarn) will get you 50, then frame for 70 points. Cutting 'hard' items often gives negative points. Use tools wisely, they are consumed.

Then, use the 'frame' tool on these combined items; it will almost always increase their value, usually leading to 100 points. The most reliable path to 100 points is: Cut a natural-soft item (e.g., flower/sunflower), Cut an artificial-soft item (e.g., paper), Combine them, then Frame the result.

message: To succeed, prioritize combining items with similar features (e.g., all natural, all artificial). The highest scores come from 'soft' and 'artificial' items: combine them, then use scissors, then use the frame. For example, 'ribbon + yarn', then 'scissors', then 'frame' yields ~70 points. 'Leaf + paper', then 'scissors', then 'frame' can yield 100 points. Be cautious with 'hard' and 'natural' items; cutting them often results in negative values that are not significantly improved by framing. message: Hello future crafter! I found that following the previous player's hints was key to success. The most reliable high-scoring pattern was: Combine two relevant ingredients -> Use Scissors on the combined item -> Use Frame on the cut combined item. Pay close attention to ingredient features (natural/artificial, soft/hard). Sometimes you can substitute ingredients if you don't have the exact one mentioned in a hint (e.g., thread for ribbon, cardboard for paper), especially if they share a feature like 'soft'. Be cautious when cutting 'hard' individual items, as they can sometimes lead to negative values. Aim for 100 and submit!
